Web Check-In - The Inside Scoop










 


Should You Check-In Online or At the Airport?



Other advantages include:

In addition to being able to hold on to your seat, on-line check-in gives you more flexibility in seat assignments. The week prior to departure is often full of seat changes, as travelers move around the plane getting upgraded and finding the best seats. At the twenty four hour window, better seats can also open up.  
Printing your boarding pass ahead of time, of course, saves time. But if you don’t have a printer, you can show an airline agent at the airport your ID and they’ll print it out for you. Some airlines offer the option of downloading your boarding pass to a mobile device or a self-service kiosk to print it out.  
Some airlines offer bonus frequent flyer miles for Web check-in.
Web Check-in is a service that allows you to check in for your flight from anywhere there’s an Internet connection. In most cases, you can select your seats and check in from 24 hours up until 2 hours before your flight. And if your itinerary includes a connection to a carrier that the airline has an e-ticketing and online check-in agreement with, you may check in for your flights with those carriers as well.
The majority of sizeable domestic airlines offer Web Check-in, including Delta, United, US Airways, American, Northwest, Continental, Alaska,  Jet Blue and Southwest. Some major international airlines also feature Web Check-in, including Air Canada, British Airways and Virgin Atlantic. However, not all international airlines have adopted the system.
While checking in online is a great time saver, like so many online exchanges, there are drawbacks. It’s a good idea to be aware of both the pros and the cons before you take the Web Check-in plunge.

Have a tip to share?Email us at hello@egencia.com.
What’s so great about it?
One of the best things about Web Check-in is that you can arrive at the airport much closer to take-off. You just need to be at the gate by the time the door is closed, 20 to 25 minutes before departure. Typically, those who are last to check in at the airport are the first to get bumped if the flight is overbooked. However, with online check-in you can lose your keys, forget your wallet, drive back home to retrieve it, get stuck in traffic, arrive at the airport just in the nick of time, and your seat still won’t be given away. Even if you don't make it at all,  your seat will be held until the last possible moment. Only if you haven't showed up at that point and the spare seats are needed will the airline give away your seat. 
Okay, so what’s not so great?
While some people have concerns about how or when they're going to check their luggage in and are worried about its integration into the system when they check-in online, that really is a non-issue. The biggest restriction is that once you check in, you cannot make any changes to your reservation. So, if your plans could change online check-in is not a good fit for your travel plans. Once you check-in, an airline imposed change fee will be applied. You'll also need to call an Egencia Travel Agent to contact the airline for you and cancel the check in. 
Additionally, you may not be eligible to use Online Flight Check-In if you are:

traveling on a military fare 
traveling with a pet
traveling with an oxygen container 
traveling with an infant under the age of two
An unaccompanied minor


About  the Author
Jennifer  Carrara is a writer for Egencia. Her background includes positions as an  advertising copywriter, marketing writer, and magazine editor. Currently she  writes proposals, answering every question in the book about the value of a  travel management partner – from how to redeem an unused airline ticket, to  configuring a global travel program.




If you travel with only carry-on luggage, boarding is further streamlined. But even if you need to check your bags, most carriers have separate lines at ticketing for "full" versus "luggage only" check-in. The "luggage only" line always moves faster because all you have to do is scan your boarding pass, drop off your bags and head through security. 

Things to Keep in Mind when you Check-in

Web Check-in is not available on all itineraries, and it isn't always perfectly clear which those might be, as they vary by airline and international law. Most airline Web sites maintain a FAQ list clearly outlining policies and restrictions.  
When traveling multiple leg trips on a single itinerary, you will be prompted to print individual boarding passes for each leg.

To Check-in Online, or Not, that is the Question
If your itinerary is complex, you might be better off checking in at the airport. But if your travel plans are straightforward, checking in online is a simple procedure that you would do well to adopt.  Not only will you save time, but you will not contribute to the long lines and subsequent long wait that other travelers who need extra assistance must endure. All in all, Web Check-in is a great choice for the Web savvy traveler.

Pros of Web Check-In:Saves time - you can arrive at the airport closer to take-off Less likely to get bumped - your seat will be held until the last possible momentMore flexibility with seat assignmentsBonus frequent flyer points with some airlinesCons of Web Check-In:You can no longer change your flight  without a change fee - you essentially cash in your ticket when you check-in onlineNot all itineraries will be eligible for online check-in, varies based on airline's policy and complexity of trip

You will not be able to check-in online for your return trip at the same time you check-in for your outbound flight unless your return flight is within 24 hours of departure. 
It’s a good idea to have more than one contact phone number, and a contact phone number for the destination you are at in case of a delay or cancellation for your return flight. Otherwise, the airline has no way to contact you. 
Rules on how long in advance of your flight you can check in vary considerably. Some airlines allow passengers to check-in online within 12-24 hours of departure time to as late as 30 minutes prior to scheduled departure time. Others require that check-in occur on the actual day of travel, meaning after 12:01AM on the day of travel, and these airlines may stop accepting online check-ins at 60 to 180 minutes before flight time. Since international travel generally requires that you arrive at your gate earlier than domestic travel, check-in deadlines are often earlier online as well. 




















